# Broch with-postgres + Caddy production configuration
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#   # edit .env
#   docker compose up -d --build


# ── Required ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Broch master key — the at-rest encryption root. Required; the server won't
# start without it. Generate a strong random value: `openssl rand -base64 48`.
BROCH_MASTER_KEY=

# Wildcard DNS hostname for tunnels and the API. Caddy issues both an apex
# cert (e.g. tunnels.example.com) and a wildcard cert (*.tunnels.example.com)
# rooted here, so this hostname must:
#   1. Be a real DNS name you control
#   2. Resolve to this host's public IP (apex A/AAAA record)
#   3. Have its DNS managed by Cloudflare (or swap the DNS provider — see
#      Caddy.Dockerfile and Caddyfile)
BROCH_WILDCARD_HOSTNAME=tunnels.example.com

# Email address Let's Encrypt notifies if your certs are about to expire and
# fail to renew. Use one you actually check.
CADDY_ACME_EMAIL=

# Cloudflare API token with Zone:Read + DNS:Edit permissions, scoped to the
# zone for BROCH_WILDCARD_HOSTNAME. Create at:
#   https://dash.cloudflare.com/profile/api-tokens
# Use the "Edit zone DNS" template. (Default provider in tls.caddy.)
CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=

# Other DNS-01 providers — all modules are compiled into the broch-caddy image; pick ONE by
# switching the `dns ...` block in tls.caddy, then set that provider's vars and leave the rest
# empty. These are for CERT ISSUANCE ONLY, never user sign-in (login is the AUTHENTICATION__*
# values further down).
# Azure DNS — AZURE_DNS_RESOURCE_GROUP is the resource group holding the DNS zone.
#   Managed identity (subscription + resource group only, no secret — grant the host's identity
#   the "DNS Zone Contributor" role on the zone):
# AZURE_DNS_SUBSCRIPTION_ID=
# AZURE_DNS_RESOURCE_GROUP=
#   Service principal (add these to the above — an app registration instead of a managed identity):
# AZURE_DNS_TENANT_ID=
# AZURE_DNS_CLIENT_ID=
# AZURE_DNS_CLIENT_SECRET=
# AWS Route 53 — standard AWS SDK env names (kept verbatim so the SDK recognizes them); an IAM
# principal with list+change rights on the hosted zone. Route 53 DNS only:
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# Google Cloud DNS — GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS is the standard Google ADC env var (a path
# to a service-account JSON with roles/dns.admin, mounted into the caddy container); GCP_PROJECT
# is the project hosting the DNS zone:
# GCP_PROJECT=
# GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS=/etc/caddy/certs/gcp-sa.json
# DigitalOcean — personal access token with write scope on DNS:
# DO_AUTH_TOKEN=

# Postgres password. Generate with `openssl rand -base64 32`.
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=

# Optional. The VM appliance pins COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME=broch so its container + named-volume names are
# stable (broch-postgres-1, broch_postgres_data) -- the README's backup / `docker exec` commands assume
# those. A docker-direct stack instead derives the project name from this directory
# (with-postgres-postgres-1). Uncomment to match the appliance's names. Set it from the START: changing
# it on a stack that already has data renames the volumes, so Postgres would start empty.
# COMPOSE_PROJECT_NAME=broch


# ── Identity provider (required at boot) ─────────────────────────────────────
#
# Broch authenticates every user through your IdP — there is no built-in local
# login, so the IdP is part of the boot floor. The server starts without these,
# but no one can sign in (or finish first-run setup) until they're set. Your
# first admin is whoever signs in holding a role named in ADMINROLES.
# Setup guides: https://broch.io/docs/identity-providers/

# Provider: Auth0 | AzureAd | EntraExternalId | Okta | Oidc
# (No inline comments after values — dotenv passes them through as part of
# the value and the server rejects it at boot.)
AUTHENTICATION__PROVIDER=
AUTHENTICATION__CLIENTID=
AUTHENTICATION__CLIENTSECRET=
# broch_admin is an example — replace with admin group(s)/role(s) from your
# own IdP that your first admin actually holds. Comma-separated; holding any
# listed role grants admin.
AUTHENTICATION__ADMINROLES=broch_admin

# Set the value(s) your provider needs; leave the rest blank:
#   Auth0 / Okta:     AUTHENTICATION__DOMAIN=your-tenant.auth0.com
#   AzureAd / Entra:  AUTHENTICATION__TENANTID + AUTHENTICATION__INSTANCE=https://login.microsoftonline.com/
#   Oidc (generic):   AUTHENTICATION__AUTHORITY=https://issuer.example.com
#   Auth0 RBAC:       AUTHENTICATION__AUDIENCE=<your-api-identifier>  (only if roles arrive via the access token)
AUTHENTICATION__DOMAIN=
AUTHENTICATION__TENANTID=
AUTHENTICATION__INSTANCE=
AUTHENTICATION__AUTHORITY=
AUTHENTICATION__AUDIENCE=


# ── Optional ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Broch license is activated in-app on first sign-in (Admin → License) — there's
# no env var for it. Buy a license at https://broch.io/pricing.

# Broch server image tag. Pin to a specific version in production.
# BROCH_VERSION=latest
# Image repo defaults to the public ghcr.io/broch-io/broch. Override only for a private mirror
# or a pre-release/beta image you've been granted (then `docker login` to that registry first):
# BROCH_IMAGE=ghcr.io/broch-io/broch

# Postgres database name and user.
# POSTGRES_DB=brochdb
# POSTGRES_USER=broch
